data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you had in .NET 10 (e.g., `options.UseCosmos(..., c => c.AllowSynchronousIO())`) no longer exists.

All synchronous LINQ operators and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throw **`InvalidOperationException`** unconditionally.

### What you must change

Every sync call needs its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key migration steps

1. **Remove** the `AllowSynchronousIO()` / sync-over-async option from your `DbContext` configuration — it won't compile.
2. **Replace** `ToList`, `First`, `Single`, `Count`, `Any`, `SaveChanges`, etc. with their `*Async` counterparts.
3. **Propagate `async/await`** up through callers (controllers, services) — this tends to cascade.
4. For `First` → consider `FirstOrDefaultAsync` where appropriate to avoid exceptions on missing data.

The Cosmos SDK has always been async-only; EF Core is now enforcing that rather than hiding it.
